* Always write in **Markdown + GitBook block syntax** (no UI-specific instructions)
* Maintain a **logical hierarchy** of pages; use headings (`#`, `##`, `###`) to structure
* Use **relative links** to other pages or anchors, e.g. `[Some Page](../other-page.md)` or `[Section](#section-anchor)`
* Use the **`tabs` block** when you have multiple variants (e.g. OS, languages, versions)

  ```md
  {% tabs %}
  {% tab title="Variant A" %}
  … content …
  {% endtab %}
  {% tab title="Variant B" %}
  … content …
  {% endtab %}
  {% endtabs %}
  ```
* Use the **`stepper` block** for step-by-step instructions or flows

  ```md
  {% stepper %}
  {% step %}
  ### Step 1
  Content…
  {% endstep %}
  {% step %}
  ### Step 2
  Content…
  {% endstep %}
  {% endstepper %}
  ```
* Use **expandable (`<details>` / `<summary>`)** blocks to hide extra detail, long examples, or FAQ content

  ```md
  <details>
  <summary>More details</summary>

  Additional content goes here.

  </details>
  ```
* Use **hint / callout blocks** for tips, warnings, important notes

  ```md
  {% hint style="warning" %}
  This is a warning or caution message.
  {% endhint %}
  ```

  (Styles: `info`, `success`, `warning`, `danger`) ([gitbook.com][1])
* Use **code blocks** with appropriate options (caption, line numbers, wrapping)

  ````md
  {% code title="example.js" overflow="wrap" lineNumbers="true" %}
  ```javascript
  // your code here
  ````

  {% endcode %}

  ```
  ```
* Use **images and figures** with captions, and optionally dark/light variants

  ```md
  ![](https://example.com/image.png)  
  <figure>
    <img src="light.png" alt="Alt text">
    <figcaption>Caption</figcaption>
  </figure>
  ```
* Use **cards** to surface related pages or modules visually (title, description, link, optional cover image)
* Use **tables** for structured comparative data, but avoid nesting tables inside non-tab blocks (tables are best used in tabs)
* Make blocks **full width** when readability is improved (e.g. large code, images, tables, cards)
* Use standard Markdown features: lists (`-`, `*`, `1.`), blockquotes (`>`), horizontal rules (`---`) ([gitbook.com][2])
* Avoid nesting disallowed blocks (e.g. a `stepper` inside another `stepper`)
* In longer docs, use **cards** or **tabs** to link to related pages rather than burying links in paragraphs
* Keep tone consistent, use concise sentences, and prefer active voice
* Avoid using emojis
* You can find extended documentation in gitbook-components.md file (inside dev folder)
